3.1 Comment on the plots

From the plot of survival time against speed, we see that there may be a weak, negative relationship between speed and survival time - Survival time tends to decrease as speed increases.

From the plot of log(survival time) against speed, we see evidence that there is an exponentially decreasing trend in survival time as speed increases. Comparing high and low experience we see that both show similar trends, but the slope of points with high experience might be slightly shallower. Points with high experience also tend to have higher survival times.

Because there appears to be an exponential trend, I took a log of the Survival Times

4.1 Method and Assumption Checks:

From our exploratory analysis we saw that there was an exponentially decreasing trend in the data so we logged the Survival Times.

We first fitted a linear model with interaction between Experience and Survival Time. However, the interaction term was insignificant with \(Pr(>F) = 0.336\). Therefore, we can simplify the model by discarding the interaction term. There were no issues with any of the assumptions of the additive model.

Our model is \[ log(Time_i) = \beta_0 + speed_i\times\beta_1 + Experience_i\times\beta_2 +\epsilon_i\]

Where \(Time_i=\) the survival time of the \(i_{th}\) player, \(Speed_i\) was their speed and \(Experience_i=1\) if they have a low experience level and 0 otherwise, and \(\epsilon_i ~\overset{iid}{\sim}\) \(N(0,\sigma^2)\)

However, this model only explains about 66% of the variation in the data.

4.2 Executive summary

We collected data on the time that players survived in a computer game in order to find out how the speed of the game affected the difficulty. We also wanted to see if being experienced with the game changed how the speed and difficulty were related.

We found that speed decreased the average survival time by the same amount, regardless of the players experience.

We estimate that median survival time decreased by between 13.6% and 16.4% for each increase in the speed setting, for both experienced and inexperienced players.

However, we also estimate that the median survival time of inexperienced players was between 22.2% and 34.1% lower than the survival time of highly experienced players.

5.5 Method and Assumption Checks: FINAL MODEL ONLY

We fitted the model: \[Fail.rate_{ijk} = \mu + Spec_i+Duration_j+\gamma_{ij} + \epsilon_{ijk} \] Where \(\mu\) is the overall mean, \(Spec_i\) are the specification grade effects, \(Duration_j\) are the duration effects, \(\gamma_{ij}\) are the interaction effects, and \(\epsilon_{ijk} ~\overset{iid}{\sim}\) \(N(0,\sigma^2)\).

5.6 Executive Summary

A study was carried out into the effectiveness of various quality inspection processes. We wanted to know how varying procedures and specifications affected the failure rate of transistors examined.

We were interested in how the testing duration affected failure rate, and if the effect of duration depended on the quality control specification in place.

We found evidence that the effect of testing duration on failure rate did change depending on which QC specification was being used.

  • For the Full Military specification, the failure rate of a short test was between 1.12 and 2.82 (per thousand transformers) higher than the failure rate of a long test.

  • For the Reduced Military specification, the failure rate of a short test was between 0.54 and 2.24 (per thousand transformers) higher than the failure rate of a long test.

  • For the commercial specification, the failure rate of a short test was between 0.55 higher and 1.15 lower (per thousand transformers) than the failure rate of a long test.

The lines are roughly parallel, indicating that there is probably no interaction between poison type and treatment type.

6.5 Describe the steps in your model building process and why you took them

I noticed that there were two factors, poison type and treatment type, with 2 and 3 levels respectively. This means that the first factor will need one dummy variable and the second will need two. I decided to re-factor the data-set to make treatment B the baseline, since it was the largest.

Using poison one and treatment B as the baselines I defined dummy variables \(Poison2_i, TreatmentA_i, TreatmentC_i\), where Poison2 equals 1 if Poison 2 is used and zero otherwise, TreatmentB equals 1 if treatment B is applied and zero otherwise, etc.

I checked a 2-way ANOVA that included an interaction variable and found that the interaction term was not significant, with \((P = 0.91)\) . That means that we have a simple additive model:\[ SurvivalTime_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1\times Poison2_i + \beta_2\times TreatmentA_i + \beta3\times TreatmentC_i + \epsilon_i\]

Where \(\epsilon_i \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0,\sigma^2)\).

However, when checking this new model I found that the poison factor was also not significant, since \((P = 0.125, > 0.1)\). This reduced the model down to a one-way ANOVA, with formula: \[SurvivalTime_i = \beta_0 + \beta_2\times TreatmentA_i + \beta3\times TreatmentC_i + \epsilon_i\] Where \(\epsilon_i \overset{iid}{\sim} N(0,\sigma^2)\).

After checking assumptions, everything seemed valid. I used confint and summary1way to generate coefficients for my model.

6.6 Executive Summary

We conducted experiments on how long animals would survive, when exposed to one of 2 poisons and treated with one of 3 treatments.

We found there also was no evidence to say that the treatments had different effects depending on which poison was applied. There also wasnt enough evidence to say if the two poisons had a different effect on survival time- this might be because the experiment size was too small.

Treatment B was the most effective by far, followed by treatments C and then A.

We estimate that treatment B on average resulted in a survival time that was between:

  • 3 hours 15 minute and 6 hours 16 minutes longer than treatment A

  • One hour 56 minutes and 4 hours 57 minutes longer than treatment C
